# Feature-first Architecture

## Structure

Each feature follows the same structure.

```text
lib/features/<feature>/
├── data/
│   ├── datasources/
│   ├── models/
│   ├── repositories/
│   └── mappers/
├── di/
│   ├── play_move_use_case_provider.dart   # @riverpod wiring — one file per provider
│   └── game_repository_provider.dart
├── domain/
│   ├── entities/
│   ├── repositories/
│   └── usecases/                          # plain Dart only — no Riverpod
├── navigation/
│   ├── <feature>_routes.dart
│   ├── <feature>_navigation.dart
│   └── <feature>_navigation_impl.dart
└── presentation/
    ├── notifiers/
    │   └── <feature>_notifier.dart        # @riverpod Notifier
    ├── widgets/
    └── <feature>_view.dart

```

---

## Dependency Rule

Dependencies always point toward the domain.

```text
Presentation → DI → Domain ← Data
```

- Presentation depends on Domain (and consumes providers wired in `di/`).
- `di/` wires Use Cases and Repositories — imports Domain + Data, never Presentation.
- Data depends on Domain by implementing repository abstractions.
- Domain depends on nothing.

Never the opposite.

---

## Layer Responsibilities

### Presentation

Responsible for:

- UI rendering
- User interactions
- UI state management

Must never contain:

- business logic
- repository implementations
- persistence logic

---

### Notifier

The Notifier never accesses repositories directly.
All business interactions go through Use Cases.

Responsible for:

- exposing immutable UI state
- orchestrating Use Cases
- requesting navigation

Must never contain:

- business rules
- business validation
- persistence logic

---

### Domain

Responsible for:

- business rules
- entities
- repository abstractions
- use cases

The domain must never import:

- Flutter
- Riverpod
- GoRouter
- platform SDKs

---

### Data

Responsible for:

- persistence
- external APIs
- local storage
- DTOs
- mapping

Must never contain:

- business logic
- business validation

---

### DI (`di/`)

Feature-level composition root. Wires domain Use Cases and Repository implementations via `@riverpod`.

Responsible for:

- declaring Use Case providers (`play_move_use_case_provider.dart`)
- declaring Repository / DataSource providers
- injecting dependencies into constructors

Must never contain:

- business logic
- UI code
- Riverpod inside `domain/` (providers live here, not in domain)

See `riverpod-providers.mdc`.

---

## Use Cases

A Use Case represents exactly one business action. Plain Dart class in `domain/usecases/`, no Flutter, no Riverpod.

### Shape

One public method: `execute`. Returns `Result<T>`. Dependencies injected via constructor (repository abstractions only).

```dart
final class PlayMoveUseCase {
  const PlayMoveUseCase();

  Result<Game> execute({required Game game, required int cellIndex}) {
    if (!game.canPlayAt(cellIndex)) {
      return const Result.failure(InvalidMoveError());
    }
    final updated = game.applyMove(cellIndex);
    return Result.success(updated);
  }
}

```

No interface required for Use Cases unless multiple implementations exist. File name = class name in snake_case (`play_move_use_case.dart`).

### Project map

| Feature | Use Case | Role |
| --- | --- | --- |
| `home` | `HasSavedGameUseCase` | Check if a saved game exists (TIC-1) |
| `game` | `StartGameUseCase` | Create a new game — reads difficulty via `SettingsRepository` (TIC-2) |
| `game` | `ResumeGameUseCase` | Load saved game via `GameRepository` |
| `game` | `PlayMoveUseCase` | Validate + apply human move + detect win/draw (TIC-3, TIC-5, TIC-9) |
| `game` | `ComputeAiMoveUseCase` | Pick AI cell from board + difficulty (TIC-8) |
| `game` | `SaveGameUseCase` | Persist game after each change (TIC-7) |
| `settings` | `GetDifficultyUseCase` | Read AI difficulty |
| `settings` | `SetDifficultyUseCase` | Save difficulty — applies to **next** game only (TIC-8) |

### Where business logic lives

| Logic | Location |
| --- | --- |
| Win / draw detection | Domain — inside `Game` / `Board` entity, called by `PlayMoveUseCase` |
| Invalid move rules | Domain — `PlayMoveUseCase` + entity guards (`canPlayAt`, `isAiTurn`, `isFinished`) |
| AI algorithm (easy / hard) | Domain — `ComputeAiMoveUseCase` + strategy per `Difficulty` enum |
| Auto-save timing | Notifier orchestrates — calls `SaveGameUseCase` after a successful move |
| AI turn sequencing | Notifier orchestrates — human move → `ComputeAiMoveUseCase` → apply AI move |
| AI move delay (UX) | Notifier — `Future.delayed` before applying AI move, not in Use Case |

The Notifier sequences Use Cases; it never implements rules itself.

### Rules

- one responsibility per Use Case
- no orchestration inside a Use Case (no calling another Use Case)
- never depend on another Use Case — share logic via **entities** instead
- never import Flutter, Riverpod, GoRouter or platform SDKs

### Testability

Win/draw and invalid moves are tested with **Use Case unit tests** and plain domain objects in Arrange — no mocks needed for board logic. See `testing.mdc`.

```dart
test('detects horizontal win on top row', () {
  final game = Game.fromBoard(['X', 'X', null, ...]);
  final result = useCase.execute(game: game, cellIndex: 2);
  expect(result, isA<Success<Game>>());
  expect(switch (result) {
    Success(:final value) => value.status,
    Failure() => fail('expected success'),
  }, GameStatus.won);
});
```

### Domain entity vs UI state

- **`Game`**, **`Board`**, **`Difficulty`** — domain entities in `domain/entities/` (manual or `freezed`).
- **`GameState`** — presentation UI state in `presentation/` (`freezed`), wraps `Game` + UI fields (`error`, `isAiThinking`).

The Notifier maps `Result<Game>` from Use Cases into `GameState`.

---

## Repository

Repositories abstract data access.
Repositories coordinate one or more data sources.
They never expose persistence details.

They are responsible for:

- loading
- saving
- mapping

They never contain business rules.

---

## View / Notifier

The View observes state through Riverpod providers.
User interactions are forwarded to the Notifier.

The View only:

- renders UI
- forwards user actions

The Notifier:

- exposes immutable UI state
- orchestrates UseCases
- exposes commands to the View

---

## Immutability

Domain entities are immutable.
Never mutate an entity in place.
Always create a new instance.

---

## Single Source of Truth

Each business state has a single source of truth.
Never duplicate state that can be derived.

---

## Feature Isolation

A feature must not directly depend on another feature.

Forbidden:

- importing another feature's **Notifier** or **View**
- importing another feature's **routes** or navigation paths

Allowed:

- domain repository abstractions from another feature (e.g. `SettingsRepository` in `settings/domain/`)
- `ref.watch(settingsRepositoryProvider)` in `game/di/` to wire a Use Case — DI composition only, never in Notifier or View directly

Prefer shared contracts in `core/` when multiple features depend on the same abstraction (e.g. `Difficulty` enum).

### Cross-feature via domain abstractions

A feature may depend on **another feature's domain repository abstraction**, never its Notifier, providers or routes.

Example — `StartGameUseCase` needs AI difficulty from settings:

```dart
// settings/domain/repositories/settings_repository.dart
abstract interface class SettingsRepository {
  Future<Result<Difficulty>> getDifficulty();
}

// game/di/start_game_use_case_provider.dart
@riverpod
StartGameUseCase startGameUseCase(Ref ref) {
  return StartGameUseCase(ref.watch(settingsRepositoryProvider));
}

```

`settingsRepositoryProvider` is declared in `settings/di/`. `Difficulty` lives in `core/` or `settings/domain/entities/`.

---

## Navigation

Each feature owns its routes under `navigation/`.

Rules:

- routes are declared as `GoRoute` (or `RouteBase`) constants/builders in `<feature>_routes.dart`
- a feature exposes its routes for aggregation by the app-level router (see `navigation.mdc`)
- a feature never references another feature's route paths directly; use route names/constants exposed by `core` or the app router

---

## Error Handling

Use a simple typed `Result<T>` sealed class, no external package.

```dart
sealed class Result<T> {
  const Result();

  const factory Result.success(T value) = Success<T>;
  const factory Result.failure(AppError error) = Failure<T>;
}
```

Avoid:

- `Future.error("...")`
- throwing `String`
- silent failures

---

## Initialization

Constructors must not perform side effects.

For Notifiers, initialization happens in `build()`, never in the constructor.

For plain classes, initialization must be explicit (e.g. `init()`) rather than performed as a constructor side effect.

---

## Testing

Mock only domain abstractions.

Unit tests must not depend on:

- Flutter
- local persistence
- platform APIs
- external services
